## Who Classified the Biogeographic Realms?

This is frequently tested directly.

**P.L. Sclater (1858)** — a British ornithologist (bird scientist) who first noticed that birds of the world could be grouped into 6 distinct regions. He was the first to define the zoogeographic regions based on bird distribution.

**Alfred Russel Wallace (1876)** — the co-discoverer of evolution by natural selection (with Darwin). He expanded Sclater's work to all animals and published "The Geographical Distribution of Animals." He is called the **"Father of Biogeography."** His 6 realms are still the standard framework.

The boundary between the **Oriental** and **Australian** realms — running between Bali and Lombok, and between Borneo and Sulawesi in Indonesia — is called the **Wallace Line**, named in his honour. West of this line: Asian animals (tigers, elephants, orangutans). East of it: Australian animals (marsupials, cockatoos). The contrast is dramatic even though the islands are only a few kilometres apart — because the deep Lombok Strait was never a land bridge even during ice ages when sea levels dropped.

