## The 6 Wallace Realms — Deep Explanation

### 1. Nearctic Realm

**Geography:** North America north of tropical Mexico, Greenland, and the northern part of the Mexican plateau.

**Climate range:** Arctic tundra in the north, temperate forests and grasslands in the middle, Mediterranean scrub in California, subtropical in the south.

**Key fauna:** American bison, pronghorn antelope, mule deer, turkey, rattlesnakes, alligators (SE USA), prairie dogs, wolverine, moose, grizzly bear, bald eagle.

**Key flora:** Redwood and sequoia forests (tallest trees on Earth), temperate deciduous forests, Great Plains grassland (prairie), boreal conifer forest.

**Biogeographic connection:** The Nearctic and Palearctic together form the **Holarctic** — because North America and Eurasia were connected via the **Bering Land Bridge** (Beringia) during ice ages when sea levels fell. This is why both realms share large mammals like bears, wolves, beavers, and deer. Humans also entered the Americas from Asia via this bridge ~15,000–20,000 years ago.

**Unique feature:** Many large Pleistocene megafauna (mammoths, mastodons, giant ground sloths, horses, camels) went extinct in North America around 10,000 BCE — likely a combination of climate change and overhunting by arriving humans.

---

### 2. Neotropical Realm

**Geography:** Central America (south of Mexico), all of South America, the Caribbean islands.

**Climate range:** Tropical rainforest (Amazon basin), tropical dry forest, savanna (cerrado and llanos), Atacama desert (driest on Earth), Patagonian steppe, Andes mountains (tallest outside Asia).

**Key fauna:** Jaguar, tapir, capybara (world's largest rodent), anaconda, poison dart frogs, toucans, macaws, hummingbirds, sloths, armadillos, anteaters, llamas, alpacas, condor, piranha, electric eel.

**Key flora:** Amazon rainforest (contains ~10% of all species on Earth), bromeliad epiphytes, tree ferns, cinchona tree (quinine source), rubber tree, cacao tree, potato, tomato, maize (all originated here).

**Why so biodiverse?** South America was an island continent for about 30 million years (after separating from Africa) until it joined North America ~3 million years ago via the **Isthmus of Panama** (the Great American Biotic Interchange). During its long isolation, it evolved completely unique fauna — giant ground sloths, terror birds, glyptodonts. When North American fauna came south (big cats, horses, tapirs, deer) they largely displaced the endemic South American fauna. But tropical conditions allowed the Amazon to accumulate extraordinary diversity.

**JRF point:** The Neotropical realm has the richest vertebrate diversity on Earth. The Amazon alone contains ~10% of all known species. It is under severe threat from deforestation (cattle ranching, soy farming).

---

### 3. Palearctic Realm

**Geography:** The largest realm. Covers all of Europe, Asia north of the Himalayas and the Yangtze River, North Africa (including Sahara), Middle East, and the northern Atlantic islands.

**Climate range:** Mediterranean (southern Europe), temperate broadleaf forest (central Europe), boreal taiga (Russia, Scandinavia), steppe/grassland (Central Asia), desert (Gobi, Sahara, Arabian), Arctic tundra (Siberia).

**Key fauna:** European bison (wisent), wolf, brown bear, lynx, red deer, reindeer/caribou, Siberian tiger, snow leopard, Bactrian camel, yak, giant panda, Siberian crane, Caspian seal.

**Key flora:** Temperate deciduous forests (oak, beech, maple), coniferous taiga (larch, spruce, pine — world's largest land biome), Mediterranean shrubland (maquis), Central Asian steppe grasslands.

**Why largest realm?** Eurasia is simply the world's largest landmass, spanning from Portugal to Chukotka — covering 11 time zones. Its size and variety of climates give it the greatest habitat diversity.

**Key biogeographic boundary within it:** The **Ural Mountains** in Russia separate Europe from Asia within the Palearctic — they are not a biogeographic barrier (the realm is continuous) but a geographic one.

---

### 4. Ethiopian (Afrotropical) Realm

**Geography:** Sub-Saharan Africa, the southern tip of the Arabian Peninsula, Madagascar (sometimes treated separately as its own sub-realm).

**Climate range:** Tropical rainforest (Congo basin — second largest on Earth after Amazon), tropical savanna (East African savannas), Sahel semi-arid zone, Namib and Kalahari deserts, Cape Fynbos (South Africa — unique scrubland).

**Key fauna:** African elephant, African lion, leopard, cheetah, giraffe, hippopotamus, rhinoceros (black and white), zebra, wildebeest, gorilla, chimpanzee, bonobo, okapi, aardvark, secretary bird, ostrich, flamingo, Nile crocodile.

**Madagascar fauna (if included):** Lemurs (found nowhere else), chameleons (~half the world's species), fossas, tenrecs — extremely unique because Madagascar separated from Africa ~160 million years ago.

**Key flora:** Congo rainforest, East African acacia savanna, baobab trees, Cape Fynbos (one of the world's richest plant diversity hotspots with ~9,600 species in a small area), Ethiopian Highland forests.

**JRF point:** Africa has the world's most diverse megafauna because **it was the birthplace of humans** — African mammals co-evolved with hominids and developed wariness/resistance to human hunters. Other continents lost their megafauna when humans arrived suddenly (Americas, Australia), but Africa's animals had millions of years to co-evolve defenses.

**Sahara as a barrier:** The Sahara Desert (which was green ~10,000 years ago during the African Humid Period) now acts as a hard biogeographic barrier separating the Ethiopian realm to its south from the Palearctic realm to its north.

---

### 5. Oriental Realm

**Geography:** South Asia (India, Sri Lanka, Pakistan lowlands), Southeast Asia (Myanmar, Thailand, Malaysia, Indonesia west of Wallace Line), southern China, Philippines.

**Climate range:** Tropical monsoon forests, tropical rainforest (Western Ghats, northeast India, Borneo, Sumatra), dry deciduous forest, tropical dry zone (Deccan, Sri Lanka), mangrove coasts.

**Key fauna:** Bengal tiger, Asian elephant, Indian rhinoceros (one-horned), gaur (Indian bison), orangutan (Sumatra and Borneo), gibbon, proboscis monkey, King cobra, Komodo dragon, Indian peafowl (peacock), Indian python, gharial, Irrawaddy dolphin, giant panda (shared with Palearctic in boundary zone).

**Key flora:** Tropical moist deciduous forests (teak, sal), tropical rainforest (dipterocarp forests — tallest tropical trees), bamboo forests, mangroves, grasslands (terai of Nepal/India — home to tigers and rhinos).

**Why India is in the Oriental realm:** India's fauna and flora align with Southeast Asia, not with Europe or Central Asia. The Himalayas act as a hard barrier keeping Palearctic fauna (wolf, snow leopard, yak) in the north and Oriental fauna (tiger, elephant, peacock) in the peninsular south and east.

**Interesting geological history:** India was part of Gondwana, separated, and drifted northward as an "island continent" for ~50 million years before colliding with Asia (~50 mya). During its drift, it carried its own unique Gondwanan fauna. After collision, it exchanged species with Asia — giving India a mix of old Gondwanan lineages and newer Asian immigrants. This makes Indian biodiversity exceptionally rich.

---

### 6. Australian Realm

**Geography:** Australia, New Guinea (Papua), New Zealand, and the Pacific islands east of the Wallace Line.

**Climate range:** Tropical rainforest (Queensland), temperate forest (southeastern Australia, New Zealand), arid desert (75% of Australia is arid or semi-arid — the Great Outback), Mediterranean scrub (southwestern Australia), alpine (New Zealand Alps, Australian Alps).

**Key fauna:** Kangaroo, wallaby, wombat, koala, Tasmanian devil, platypus, echidna, emu, cassowary, kiwi, kakapo, lyrebird, cockatoo, blue-tongued lizard, saltwater crocodile (shared with Oriental), box jellyfish.

**Key flora:** Eucalyptus (dominates ~75% of Australian forests — over 700 species), Acacia (wattle — national flower of Australia), Banksia, Grevillea, kauri pine (New Zealand), tree ferns.

**Why most unique realm:**

Australia separated from Antarctica (and thus from Gondwana) approximately **50–45 million years ago**, making it the longest-isolated major landmass. Mammals had already diversified into placental and marsupial lineages, but when Australia separated, it took mainly **marsupials** with it. Placental mammals later reached most of the world through connected land routes, but never reached Australia naturally (except bats which flew, and rodents which rafted ~5 mya).

Australia therefore shows the most dramatic example of **convergent evolution** — marsupials evolved to fill the same ecological niches that placentals fill elsewhere: the Tasmanian wolf parallels the wolf, the marsupial mole parallels the mole, the sugar glider parallels the flying squirrel. Same niches, completely unrelated animals — this is one of the most powerful demonstrations of natural selection.

**Monotremes** (platypus, echidna) — the only egg-laying mammals on Earth — are found only in the Australian realm. They represent the most ancient lineage of mammals.

