## Beyond Wallace: Other Classification Systems

### Udvardy's Biogeographic Provinces (1975) — Very Important for NET

While Wallace defined **Realms** (large), **Miklos Udvardy (1975)** working with UNESCO divided the world into **193 biogeographic provinces** — much finer subdivisions within each realm. This system is used in conservation planning and is frequently referenced in UGC NET questions.

Udvardy's provinces are defined by **biome type within a realm** — so the "Maulino Forest" province is the temperate forest province within the Neotropical realm, while the "Brazilian Rainforest" province is the tropical rainforest province in the same realm.

**India's biogeographic provinces under Udvardy:**
India falls in the **Oriental realm** and contains several provinces including the Indo-Gangetic monsoon forest, Malabar rainforest, Deccan thorn scrub, Coromandel coast, Himalayan highlands, and others.

### WWF's Ecoregions System

The **World Wildlife Fund (WWF)** has further divided the world into **867 terrestrial ecoregions** — even finer divisions. These are used to identify conservation priorities. The "Global 200" ecoregions are the most ecologically representative and diverse.

